      "heading": "Show your AI agent only the code it needs.",
      "backgroundColor": "#0A0D0F",
      "callsToAction": [],
      "text": "Context localization for AI coding agents Show your AI agent only the code it needs. Every edit doesn't need the whole repo. Type a task and watch the irrelevant code fade out — Locus maps it to a focused dependency slice. When the evidence is weak, it conservatively falls back to the whole repo.",
      "layout": "centered",
      "assetUrls": []
    },
    {
      "selector": "section",
      "type": "content",
      "x": 0,
      "y": 1536,
      "width": 1920,
      "height": 358,
      "heading": "Replayed against fixes from real repositories",
      "backgroundColor": "#111619",
      "callsToAction": [
        "Read the method and reproduce it →"
      ],
      "text": "MEASURED, NOT PROMISED Replayed against fixes from real repositories 100% historical fix-file recall 53% median estimated context reduction 9 / 3 tasks / repositories Historical replay checks whether the context includes files developers changed next. It does not measure autonomous agent completion or guarantee that excluded files are unnecessary. Read the method and reproduce it →",
      "layout": "centered",
      "assetUrls": []
    },
    {
      "selector": "section",
      "type": "content",
      "x": 0,
      "y": 1894,
      "width": 1920,
      "height": 367,
      "heading": "1 · Map the graph",
      "backgroundColor": "#111619",
      "callsToAction": [],
      "text": "HOW IT WORKS 1 · Map the graph Parse imports into a deterministic dependency graph — routes → components → hooks → libs. No LLM guessing. 2 · Localize the task Match task language against paths and source, then include dependencies and nearby integration points. 3 · Widen when uncertain If no file matches with enough evidence, fall back to the whole repo instead of returning a speculative small slice. Cross-cutting bugs (a shared util that broke the dashboard) are caught two ways: the shared file is already in the dependency slice, and a recent-change signal floats it to the top — so precision",
      "layout": "centered",
      "assetUrls": []
    },
    {
      "selector": "#use",
      "type": "content",
      "x": 384,
      "y": 2261,
      "width": 1152,
      "height": 520,
      "heading": "Two ways to actually save tokens — not just look at a graph",
      "backgroundColor": "#0A0D0F",
      "callsToAction": [],
      "text": "USE IT FOR REAL Two ways to actually save tokens — not just look at a graph 1 · Now, in your browser Load a supported public TypeScript repo above, describe the task, and hit Copy context — you get the focused slice as a paste-ready block. Give that to ChatGPT / Claude / Cursor instead of your whole repo. Zero install. 2 · In your agent's loop (CLI + MCP) A zero-dependency CLI and MCP server run the same localizer on your local repo, so the agent pulls the slice before it reads. # one-off, paste-ready context npx github:taranggoyal70/locus \\ locate \"fix the dashboard\" --pack # as an MCP tool (",
      "layout": "centered",
      "assetUrls": []
    }
